ards/42/42027.html Scorecard]\n| venue = [[Dudley Park, Rangiora|Dudley Park]], [[Rangiora]]\n| motm =\n| toss = Australia won the toss and elected to bat.\n| notes = \n| stack = y }}\n\n==Final==\n{{main|1982 Women's Cricket World Cup Final}}\nEngland's [[Dickie Bird]], who had been specifically invited to the tournament, with his flights sponsored by [[Air New Zealand]], became the first (and, so far, only) person to umpire the final of both the men's and women's World Cups.<ref name=\"bird\"/>\n\n{{Limited Overs Matches\n| date = 7 February\n| time = \n| team1 = {{crw-rt|ENG}}\n| score1 = 151/5 (60 overs)\n| runs1 = [[Jan Southgate]] 53 (104)\n| wickets1 = [[Lyn Fullston]] 2/20 (12 overs)\n| team2 = {{crw|AUS}}\n| score2 = 152/7 (59 overs)\n| runs2 = [[Jen Jacobs]] 37 (45)\n| wickets2 = [[Avril Starling]] 2/21 (12 overs)\n| result = Australia won by 3 wickets\n| report = [https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/42/42029.html Scorecard]\n| venue = [[Lancaster Park]], [[Christchurch]]\n| umpires = [[Dickie Bird]] (Eng) and [[Fred Goodall]] (NZ)\n| motm=\n| toss = England won the toss and elected to bat.\n}}\n\n==Statistics==\n\n===Most runs===\nThe top five runscorers are included in this table, ranked by runs scored and then by [[batting average (cricket)|batting average]].\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Player !! Team !! Runs !! Inns !! Avg !! Highest !! 100s !! 50s\n|-\n| [[Jan Brittin]] || {{crw|ENG}} || '''391''' || 12 || 39.10 || 139* || 1 || 1\n|-\n| [[Lynne Thomas]] || {{noflag|[[International XI women's cricket team|International XI]]}} || '''383''' || 12 || 38.30 || 70* || 0 || 2\n|-\n| [[Susan Goatman]] || {{crw|ENG}} || '''374''' || 13 || 34.00 || 83 || 0 || 3\n|-\n| [[Jill Kennare]] || {{crw|AUS}} || '''351''' || 9 || 43.87 || 98 || 0 || 2\n|-\n| [[Barbara Bevege]] || {{crw|NZL}} || '''320''' || 10 || 32.00 || 101 || 1 || 1\n|-\n|}\nSource: [https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Events/2/Hansells_Vita_Fresh_Womens_World_Cup_1981-82/Batting_by_Runs.